  "output": "# PostgreSQL Transportation Database ‚Äî Performance Anomaly Diagnosis\r\n\r\n**One-line summary:** A 2-million-row synthetic wide table (`public.table1`, 1421 MB, 99.43% of DB, 0 indexes) is the sole source of three confirmed performance anomalies: bulk-load data insertion, unbounded full-table fetching, and absent/suppressed post-reset autovacuum maintenance.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Decision\r\n\r\nThe team selects **exactly three** root causes:\r\n\r\n1. **INSERT_LARGE_DATA**\r\n2. **FETCH_LARGE_DATA**\r\n3. **VACUUM**\r\n\r\nRuled out (binary, decisive): `LOCK_CONTENTION`, `REDUNDANT_INDEX`\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Evidence per Selected Cause\r\n\r\n### 1. INSERT_LARGE_DATA\r\n\r\n`public.table1` was loaded via a direct bulk operation (`COPY` / `pg_restore` / `INSERT‚Ä¶SELECT`), not organic application traffic.\r\n\r\n| Metric | Value |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| Actual row count | 2,000,000 |\r\n| `MIN(time)` | `2026-06-25 05:50:17.644638` |\r\n| `MAX(time)` | `2026-06-25 05:50:17.649855` |\r\n| Time span across 2M rows | **0.005217 seconds** |\r\n| Distinct timestamps | **99** |\r\n| Table total size | **1421 MB** (99.43% of entire database) |\r\n| Pages (`relpages`) | 181,821 |\r\n| Column count | 22 (`id`, `name0`‚Äì`name19`, `time`) |\r\n| Indexes on table1 | **0** |\r\n\r\n**Diagnosis:** 2,000,000 rows sharing 99 distinct timestamps across a 5.217 ms window is physically impossible under organic application write patterns. No real traffic produces this signature. The 20 sequential `nameN varchar(100)` columns confirm a synthetic data generator. The table consumes virtually the entire database at 1421 MB.\r\n\r\n**Key SQL (Fenster):**\r\n```sql\r\nSELECT COUNT(*) AS actual_rows,\r\n       MIN(time) AS min_ts, MAX(time) AS max_ts,\r\n       EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM (MAX(time)-MIN(time))) AS span_seconds,\r\n       COUNT(DISTINCT time) AS distinct_timestamps\r\nFROM public.table1;\r\n-- Result: 2000000 rows | span = 0.005217 s | 99 distinct timestamps\r\n```\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n### 2. FETCH_LARGE_DATA\r\n\r\nEvery query against `table1` performs an unindexed full sequential scan over 2,000,025 rows. The database-level I/O and temp-spill metrics confirm this is the dominant cost driver.\r\n\r\n| Metric | Value |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| `tup_returned` (pg_stat_database) | 277,020,134 |\r\n| `tup_fetched` (pg_stat_database) | 358,825 |\r\n| **Ratio returned/fetched** | **772.0 : 1** |\r\n| Cache hit rate | **26.66%** |\r\n| `blks_read` | 22,415,532 |\r\n| Temp files | **54** |\r\n| Temp bytes spilled | **~1.41 GB** (1,483,235,328 bytes) |\r\n| table1 `seq_scan` count | 264 |\r\n| table1 `seq_tup_read` | 276,000,405 |\r\n| table1 `idx_scan` | **NULL (0)** |\r\n\r\n**Top queries from `pg_stat_statements`:**\r\n\r\n| Query | Calls | Total ms | Mean ms | Shared blks_read | Temp blks written |\r\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\r\n| `SELECT count(*) FROM table1` | 42 | 83,684.9 | 1,992.5 | 6,874,444 | 0 |\r\n| `SELECT count(*), count(DISTINCT time)‚Ä¶` | 14 | 72,577.0 | 5,184.1 | 2,322,655 | 41,328 |\r\n| `SELECT count(*) AS exact_rows, min(time)‚Ä¶` | 14 | 62,856.4 | 4,489.7 | 2,269,791 | 41,328 |\r\n| `SELECT min(time)‚Ä¶count(DISTINCT time)‚Ä¶` | 17 | 39,475.9 | 2,322.1 | 2,699,728 | 50,184 |\r\n| `SELECT min(time)‚Ä¶count(*) FROM table1` | 12 | 38,225.2 | 3,185.4 | 1,849,903 | 35,424 |\r\n\r\n**Diagnosis:** A 772:1 tup_returned/tup_fetched ratio means 772 rows are read from storage for every one delivered to the client. The 26.66% cache hit rate (healthy OLTP: >95%) shows the working set far exceeds `shared_buffers`. With zero indexes on table1, every aggregation query forces a 181,821-page sequential scan; `COUNT(DISTINCT time)` queries additionally spill to disk (up to ~50 K temp_blks_written per call, 54 temp files, ~1.41 GB total spill), because `work_mem` is exhausted before the sort/hash completes in memory.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n### 3. VACUUM\r\n\r\n**Signal:** After `pg_stat_reset()` wiped all counters at `2026-06-25 21:40:57 UTC`, `pg_stat_user_tables` shows `vacuum_count=0`, `autovacuum_count=0`, `last_autovacuum=NULL`, `n_ins_since_vacuum=0` on a 2-million-row, 1.4 GB table ‚Äî 16 hours of post-reset silence with no autovacuum recorded.\r\n\r\n| Metric | Value |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| `vacuum_count` | 0 |\r\n| `autovacuum_count` | 0 |\r\n| `last_vacuum` / `last_autovacuum` | NULL |\r\n| `n_ins_since_vacuum` | 0 (zeroed by stats reset) |\r\n| `autovacuum` setting | `on` |\r\n| `autovacuum_vacuum_insert_threshold` | 1,000 |\r\n| `autovacuum_vacuum_insert_scale_factor` | 0.2 |\r\n| Computed insert-vacuum trigger | **401,005 rows** (1,000 + 0.2 √ó 2,000,025) |\r\n| Rows inserted above threshold (multiples) | ~5√ó |\r\n| Stats reset timestamp | `2026-06-25 21:40:57 UTC` |\r\n| `relpages` / `relallvisible` | 181,821 / 181,821 (100%) |\r\n| `frozen_age` | 104 |\r\n| pg_visibility extension installed | **No** |\r\n\r\n**Key SQL (Fenster):**\r\n```sql\r\nSELECT vacuum_count, autovacuum_count, n_ins_since_vacuum,\r\n       last_vacuum, last_autovacuum\r\nFROM pg_stat_user_tables WHERE relname='table1';\r\n-- vacuum_count=0, autovacuum_count=0, last_autovacuum=NULL, n_ins_since_vacuum=0\r\n\r\nSELECT stats_reset FROM pg_stat_database WHERE datname='sysbench';\r\n-- 2026-06-25 21:40:57.47372+00\r\n\r\nSELECT relpages, relallvisible FROM pg_class WHERE relname='table1';\r\n-- relpages=181821, relallvisible=181821\r\n```\r\n\r\nSee the **VACUUM Reconciliation Note** below for the full interpretive debate.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Ruled Out\r\n\r\n### LOCK_CONTENTION ‚Äî ABSENT\r\n\r\n| Check | Result |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| Total locks in `pg_locks` | 32 (all `granted=true`) |\r\n| Ungranted locks | **0** |\r\n| Sessions with `wait_event_type='Lock'` | **0** |\r\n| Blocking/blocked PID pairs | **0** |\r\n| `deadlocks` (pg_stat_database) | **0** |\r\n\r\n**Reasoning:** No process is queued behind any lock. The only non-idle session at diagnostic time was the diagnostic query itself, waiting on `DataFileRead` ‚Äî an I/O wait caused by FETCH_LARGE_DATA, categorically distinct from lock-type contention. Binary and decisive; no action required.\r\n\r\n### REDUNDANT_INDEX ‚Äî ABSENT\r\n\r\n| Check | Result |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| Total indexes in `public` schema | 11 |\r\n| Indexes on `table1` | **0** |\r\n| Tables with >1 index | `users` only (3 indexes) |\r\n| `users` index key columns | `user_id` (PK), `email` (unique), `username` (unique) ‚Äî all distinct |\r\n| Any two indexes sharing table + leading key column | **None** |\r\n\r\n**Reasoning:** `table1` cannot have redundant indexes because it has zero indexes. The `users` table's three indexes each cover a completely different column with no prefix overlap or functional duplication. The schema is *under-indexed* (specifically on table1), which is the opposite of redundancy. Binary and decisive.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## VACUUM Reconciliation Note\r\n\r\nThis section documents the active disagreement between Fenster's per-indicator finding and the team's synthesized verdict.\r\n\r\n### Fenster's argument (VACUUM = ABSENT)\r\n\r\n`pg_class.relallvisible = relpages = 181,821` (100% all-visible). In normal PostgreSQL operations, the all-visible bits in the visibility map are set exclusively by VACUUM. If every page is all-visible, vacuum must have run and completed successfully. Fenster's reconstructed timeline: bulk insert at 05:50:17 UTC ‚Üí autovacuum fires within minutes, sets all pages all-visible ‚Üí `pg_stat_reset()` at 21:40:57 UTC erases the counters.\r\n\r\n### The counter-argument (why VACUUM remains selected)\r\n\r\n1. **COPY FREEZE ambiguity.** `pg_class.relallvisible = relpages` is *also* consistent with `COPY ‚Ä¶ WITH (FREEZE)`, which marks all inserted pages as all-visible and frozen at load time ‚Äî no subsequent vacuum pass required. The `pg_visibility` extension is **not installed** in this database, so it is impossible to distinguish between \"vacuum set all-visible\" and \"COPY FREEZE set all-visible\" from catalog inspection alone. The all-visible evidence is therefore inconclusive.\r\n\r\n2. **Stats-reset suppression of autovacuum's own trigger.** `pg_stat_reset()` zeroed `n_ins_since_vacuum = 0`. Autovacuum's insert-triggered cycle computes `n_ins_since_vacuum ‚â• threshold`; after the reset this counter reads zero, so autovacuum sees no pending insert-vacuum work even though 2 M rows were inserted. This creates a suppression loop: the reset both erased the historical evidence of vacuum and reset the counter that would prompt a new vacuum cycle.\r\n\r\n3. **Post-reset autovacuum silence (16 hours).** From `2026-06-25 21:40:57 UTC` to the diagnostic run at `2026-06-26 09:16 UTC` ‚Äî approximately 16 hours ‚Äî `autovacuum_count` remains 0 and `last_autovacuum` remains NULL. On a 1.4 GB / 2-million-row table with `autovacuum=on` and `autovacuum_naptime=60s`, this extended post-reset silence is the surviving anomaly signal.\r\n\r\n4. **Forced-choice elimination.** Of the five candidate causes, LOCK_CONTENTION and REDUNDANT_INDEX are decisively absent (binary evidence). INSERT_LARGE_DATA and FETCH_LARGE_DATA are confirmed. The forced-choice rule requires exactly three. VACUUM is the only remaining candidate.\r\n\r\n### Synthesis\r\n\r\nThe team selects VACUUM as the third cause on the basis of: (a) the forced-choice constraint after binary elimination of two candidates, and (b) the post-reset autovacuum silence signal which cannot be fully explained away. The relallvisible evidence is acknowledged as ambiguous (COPY FREEZE vs. vacuum). This selection carries lower confidence than INSERT_LARGE_DATA or FETCH_LARGE_DATA; see the **Confidence** section.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Remediation\r\n\r\nPriorities are ordered by severity and immediacy.\r\n\r\n### Priority 1 ‚Äî FETCH_LARGE_DATA (critical, immediate)\r\n\r\n1. **Add an index on `table1`** to eliminate full sequential scans:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   -- Minimum: index on the time column used in all top queries\r\n   CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY ON public.table1 (time);\r\n   -- If a unique surrogate key is needed (table1 has no PK):\r\n   ALTER TABLE public.table1 ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY;\r\n   ```\r\n2. **Increase `work_mem`** to eliminate temp-file spill for `COUNT(DISTINCT ‚Ä¶)` and sort-heavy aggregations:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   -- Session-level for heavy analytical workloads:\r\n   SET work_mem = '256MB';\r\n   -- Global baseline in postgresql.conf:\r\n   work_mem = '64MB'\r\n   ```\r\n3. **Enforce LIMIT/keyset pagination** on all queries that return large result sets; never allow unbounded `SELECT *` on table1.\r\n4. **Replace exact `COUNT(*)` with estimates** where precision is not required:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   SELECT reltuples::bigint AS approx_rows FROM pg_class WHERE relname='table1';\r\n   ```\r\n5. **Consider range partitioning** by `time` if data grows continuously, enabling partition pruning to avoid cross-partition full scans.\r\n\r\n### Priority 2 ‚Äî INSERT_LARGE_DATA (architecture, before next load)\r\n\r\n1. **Break bulk loads into batches** of 50 K‚Äì100 K rows to limit single-transaction WAL pressure and table bloat.\r\n2. **Use `COPY ‚Ä¶ WITH (FREEZE)` for initial loads** to avoid a post-load vacuum pass and immediately mark all pages as all-visible:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   COPY public.table1 FROM '/path/to/data.csv' WITH (FORMAT csv, FREEZE);\r\n   ```\r\n3. **Run `ANALYZE` immediately after every bulk load** to keep planner statistics current:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   ANALYZE public.table1;\r\n   ```\r\n4. **Audit the schema.** The 20 √ó `varchar(100)` `nameN` columns are almost certainly synthetic scaffolding. Remove or rename columns to those actually queried; narrower rows reduce page count and scan cost.\r\n5. **Consider table partitioning** by time range to isolate bulk loads into individual partitions, limit full-scan scope, and enable efficient partition-level maintenance.\r\n\r\n### Priority 3 ‚Äî VACUUM (maintenance hygiene)\r\n\r\n1. **Run `VACUUM (ANALYZE, VERBOSE)` manually** on table1 to confirm state and refresh statistics post-reset:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   VACUUM (ANALYZE, VERBOSE) public.table1;\r\n   ```\r\n2. **Tune per-table autovacuum** to handle insert-heavy tables more aggressively:\r\n   ```sql\r\n   ALTER TABLE public.table1\r\n     SET (autovacuum_vacuum_insert_scale_factor = 0.05,\r\n          autovacuum_vacuum_insert_threshold    = 1000,\r\n          autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor        = 0.05,\r\n          autovacuum_vacuum_threshold           = 1000);\r\n   ```\r\n   This lowers the insert-vacuum trigger from 401,005 rows to ~101,000 rows on the current table, ensuring timely maintenance after future loads.\r\n3. **Avoid `pg_stat_reset()` in production** unless absolutely necessary, as it zeroes autovacuum counters and resets the `n_ins_since_vacuum` trigger, masking maintenance history and suppressing future autovacuum cycles.\r\n4. **Install `pg_visibility`** (`CREATE EXTENSION pg_visibility`) to enable reliable inspection of the visibility map (distinguishing COPY FREEZE from vacuum-set all-visible bits) in future diagnostics.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Confidence\r\n\r\n| Cause | Confidence | Basis |\r\n|---|---|---|\r\n| **INSERT_LARGE_DATA** | **High** | 2 M rows in 5.217 ms / 99 distinct timestamps is physically impossible without a bulk-load mechanism. 1421 MB = 99.43% of DB. Unambiguous. |\r\n| **FETCH_LARGE_DATA** | **High** | 772:1 tup_returned/tup_fetched, 26.66% cache hit, 264 seq_scans / 276 M seq_tup_read, 0 idx_scans, 54 temp files / 1.41 GB spill. Multiple independent metrics converge. |\r\n| **VACUUM** | **Medium** | Surviving signal is post-reset autovacuum silence (16 h, autovacuum_count=0) and forced-choice elimination. The relallvisible evidence is ambiguous (COPY FREEZE cannot be ruled out; pg_visibility not installed). Selection rests partly on elimination. |\r\n| **LOCK_CONTENTION** (ruled out) | **High** | 0 ungranted locks, 0 lock waiters, 0 blocking pairs, 0 deadlocks. Binary. |\r\n| **REDUNDANT_INDEX** (ruled out) | **High** | 0 indexes on table1; users' 3 indexes are all distinct; no prefix overlaps anywhere. Binary. |\r\n",
